  "Notes": [
    {
      "Id": "f0000000000000000000000000000001",
      "Text": "FLOOR OPENINGS NEEDING HANDRAILS.  Equipment (a boiler, duct, pipe) drops through an opening in the slab and leaves a gap around it; if that gap is wide enough it is a fall hazard and needs a handrail.  This graph has two parts you can use together or on their own.",
      "X": 0.0,
      "Y": -140.0
    },
    {
      "Id": "f0000000000000000000000000000002",
      "Text": "PART 1 - Does the equipment already have a handrail beside it?  1) In Navisworks, SELECT the equipment you are checking.  2) Set the three search boxes so Search.ByPropertyContains finds your handrails/guardrails.  3) Set the trigger distance (document units - chain Units.Convert for m/ft).  Run: each 'true' in the Watch is a piece of equipment with NO handrail within that distance - i.e. one that still needs one.",
      "X": 0.0,
      "Y": 600.0
    },
    {
      "Id": "f0000000000000000000000000000003",
      "Text": "PART 2 - How wide is the gap around the equipment (the 'furthest', not the nearest, edge)?  BoundingBox.PlanGap compares the opening footprint (outer) with the equipment footprint (inner) and returns the WIDEST of the four side gaps - the biggest open strip, which is what determines the hazard.  Here it reports 0.8 and flags true against the 0.5 threshold.  In your model, replace the two BoundingBox.ByCorners with ModelItem.BoundingBox of the opening and the equipment (the bbox converts automatically).",
      "X": 360.0,
      "Y": 1320.0
    }
  ],
  "Groups": [],
  "View": {
    "RunType": "Manual",
    "Camera": {
      "X": 0.0,
      "Y": 0.0,
      "Zoom": 1.0
    }
  }
}
